my 2c -&lt;br&gt;
When teaching Java, I used to quote the SUN text book: &quot;if your code
has a lot of protected methods, it is either very badly or very elegantly
designed&quot;.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;blockquote type=cite cite&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &gt; Also, I take the term
&quot;public interface&quot; as relative. If an object&lt;br&gt;
exposes an interface (set of methods)&lt;br&gt;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &gt; to its peer objects within its package, I see no
reason not to test&lt;br&gt;
it, even though those methods are&lt;br&gt;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &gt; package-protected. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
I guess I disagree here.&nbsp; I am not convinced that package-potected
methods&lt;br&gt;
are part of a public interface.&nbsp; If they are used that way I would
question&lt;br&gt;
whether some refactoring needed to take place.&nbsp; But that&#39;s just my
opinion.&lt;br&gt;
I don&#39;t want to seem like I am picking on your design
decisions.&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;br&gt;

